ly modern and modern Europe. The contributors ask whether, and in what forms, a social formation that rightfully can be called the “public sphere” really existed at particular historical junctures, and consider the senses in which the “public sphere” should rather be replaced by a multitude of interacting cultural and social “publics.” This volume offers insights into the current status of the “public sphere” within the disciplinary formation of the humanities and social sciences at the beginning of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCivil societyzEuropexHistory. 0aCommunicationxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 0aCommunicationxSocial aspectszEuropexHistory. 0aPublic opinionzEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aBoyle, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmden, Christian J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmden, Christian J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLauster, Martina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMidgley, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMidgley, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTimms, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWestphal, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhaley, Joachim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZammito, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745501740uhttp